Relinquishment/Forfeiture: modern criticisms

Any person who abandons the same, or who voluntarily fails, without sufficient cause, to beneficially use all or any part of said right to divert or withdraw for any period of five successive years shall relinquish such right or portion thereof

  • Water users face potential forfeiture if they do not use their full water, so are incentivized to be inefficient in application.
  • Also impedes water transactions, since use is not evaluated except during legal matters or seeking approval for a lease/sale.

But this begs the (research) question

What was the economic incentive for beneficial use and relinquishment/forfeiture as a policy, and how does the effect of the policy change as a basin becomes fully allocated?

Economics of the frontier

Based on work by Anderson and Hill (1975) and Anderson and Hill (1990):

  • Consider the frontier as a shockwave that passes through an area.
  • The shockwave reflects a combination of infrastructure developments that increase the productive capacity of the region.
  • In particular, previously unprofitable land may become profitable as infrastructure increases.

The frontier as a shockwave

How do we define property rights?

Prior Appropriations as a solution

  • Allocation on priority of right makes water excludable.
  • Allows for collective action (Ostrom and Gardner 1993) among cohesive groups and contracts (Leonard and Libecap 2016) among non-cohesive groups solve the problem of investment in community infrastructure.

Concerns with Prior Appropriations

  • A monopolist could charge water prices that raise \(C\) to \(V1\), extracting all profits from working the land.
  • Speculators could claim water, waiting for land prices to rise before selling it.
  • A claim holder could abandon their claim and return to it later, extracting fees for water use.

Beneficial use and forfeiture are necessary

Beneficial use and forfeiture sought to (Zellmer 2007):

  • Reduce monopoly and speculation behaviors
  • Maximize the use of a scarce resource
  • Allow flexibility of use by users

Timeline of Washington Water Law

  • 1873: Water rights and irrigation law in Yakima County
  • 1889: Washington becomes a state
  • 1890, 1891: Prior appropriation and beneficial use (claim by posting notice)
  • 1917: Water Code [RCW 90.03] (claims filed with water master)
  • 1967: Relinquishment (RCW 90.14.160)

The filing of a statement of claim pursuant to RCW 90.14.061 which knowingly provides for an overstatement of a right either in quantities of water or times of use claimed shall constitute a misdemeanor punishable by a fine of not more than two hundred fifty dollars or by imprisonment for not more than ninety days, or both.

Hypothesis: In early years, less policy and enforcement suggests that earlier claims should have a higher acre-feet to acres ratio.

Next Steps

  • Include water rights databases from other states
  • Incorporate forfeiture and its effects in the present
  • Ultimate goal: a formal model of beneficial use and forfeiture during the frontier and now, with data to test implications
